Fig. 10
 exhibits TL characteristic of the studied YAlO3: Nd3+ sample within 150–350 °C. The sample has showed maximum intensity value of TL glow curve at around 220 °C. Further, dopping Nd3+ has affected the intensity after 375 °C and a weak peak has been observed. It is thought that Nd3+ ions, which act as a luminescence center in the host crystal, cause a decrease in luminescence intensity by filling the existing atomic spaces. In order to understand the TL kinetic of YAlO3 crystal, the TL glow curve parameters (activation energy, frequency factor and kinetic order) have calculated using CGDC (Table 7
) and peak shape method (Table 8
).

The Tb3+ ion has been used as the co-dopant in YAlO3: Mn2+ phosphor and observed a significant increase of intensity when compared to the TL curve of YAlO3: Mn2+ phosphor (Fig. 12
                           ). Besides, the peak obtained at about 200 °C is thought to be a characteristic peak of Tb3+ in the host material. The lattice parameters calculated using CGDC and peak shape method have been reported in Tables 9 and 10

                           , respectively.
